Sainsbury's plans for the UK beauty products market
Sainsbury's has decided to compete at Boots, Superdrug and Debenhams with beauty product corridors in the style of busy department stores with specialized employees.
These large corridors are only part of a considerable investment in the UK beauty products market, a market that moves around GBP 28 billion and continues to grow as the fashion and household products sectors fall behind, and 11 stores across the country will be tested to expand to more stores next year.
The investment in beauty products is the product of the greed of supermarkets to take advantage of the space in their shelves that was previously intended for televisions, microwaves and household products.
Sainsbury’s says it will double its beauty offering to offer up to 3,000 different products, including for the first time brands such as Revlon, Essie, Tweezerman and Dr. PawPaw.
The existing ranges of L'Oreal, Maybelline and Burt's Bees will also receive more space with areas of similar brands that can be found in stores such as Boots.
The supermarket company is also relaunching its range of makeup products Boutique so that most products are now vegan-friendly, an aspect increasingly demanded by younger consumers.
The retail chain The Fragrance Shop will also open concessions to two Sainsbury's stores. The first did so last week in Croydon, south London, while the second will open at Selly Oak, Birmingham, later this year.
Shopping online and switching to buying food in smaller quantities every day at small supermarkets has made big supermarkets have to find other ways to convince people to come.
According to Mike Coupe, executive director of Sainsbury’s, the stores will increasingly resemble department stores in an attempt by the supermarket chain to fight discount supermarkets Aldi and Lidl with more non-food services and products.
Sainsbury's has been introducing Argos outlets to many of its supermarkets, as well as a number of Habitat stores since it acquired both chains two years ago, which, he says, has served to revive grocery sales and increase the profitability of acquisitions.
The supermarket chain’s previous attempt to relaunch its beauty and pharmacy product departments resulted in a failure.
Sainsbury's made a joint operation test with Boots in the early 2000s, but it all ended hastily by not agreeing on how to divide the benefits of the pharmacy chain within supermarkets.
This new strategy comes after Sainsbury’s sold its 281 pharmacies to Celesio, owner of the LloydsPharmacy chain, for 125 million GBP three years ago.
According to Sainsbury’s, Lloyds will play an important role in the global plan, as it will expand its range of luxury leather brands, such as La Roche-Posay and Vichy, to four stores.
Paul Mills-Hicks, Chief Commercial Officer of Sainsbury's, comments: "We have transformed the look of our beauty corridors to improve the environment for our customers.
We have invested in specifically trained workers who will be of great help in offering advice.
Our range of brands is designed to fit any need; on the other hand, the attractive environment and convenient location make us now one of the favorite destinations for beauty products and we challenge the traditional way of shopping.”
