Harvard students take a course on resting habits
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the increasingly widespread culture of studying all night long, stimulated by caffeine.
One scholar noted that students at the world’s number one university are often misguided about the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a talk about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
“At the end of the talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why do they tell me this now, all this, in my last year?’
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
In the course, implemented for the first time this year, students are explained the basic concepts on how good sleep habits improve academic and sports performance, as well as general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is a picture of a bedroom, where students must click on coffee cups, curtains, dolls and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how it affects sports performance to lack of sleep, and about the importance of maintaining a sleeping routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of staying awake all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure students face make sleep deprivation an ever-growing problem.
Making sure you enjoy good quality sleep for long enough should be a “secret weapon” for students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode and makes students always hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having attended one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course throughout the campus.
The next step, he expects, is to ask graduate students to undertake a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students take into account the fact that they set an alarm when going to sleep and when they wake up, and that they be aware of the detrimental effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can alter the harmony of the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
