Almanac: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page from the Sunday Morning Almanac: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago... the day that the physicist of the future, Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device we know as the "Geiger counter".
The Geiger counter, which has been a pillar of science ever since, also became a staple of pop culture, such as the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado", starring Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, seemingly failed cowboy physicists:
“What the hell is this?”
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, which is used to find radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you wear these headphones, you can hear the effects of the atoms emitted from radioactivity to the minerals.”
Evans: "It's definitely exploding now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days after his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name is still alive.
