The National Foundation spying on the secret life of bats
A new research carried out on a farm in the Scottish Highlands aims to discover how bats use the landscape to feed themselves.
The findings are expected to provide new data on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help with future conservation activities.
The study of scientists from the National Foundation of Scotland will follow soprano and common bats, as well as northern ear bats and water in the Inverewe Botanical Garden, located in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations of the property to track bats’ activities during the season.
Volunteers and staff of the UK National Health Service will also conduct mobile surveys with portable detectors.
The sound analysis of the recordings by experts will determine the sound frequency of bats and what each species does.
With this information, a report and a map of the habitat will be created to create a detailed landscape-scale image of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at the National Foundation of Scotland, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the advantages of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, and how to improve forest maintenance for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the rest of the United Kingdom has declined considerably in the last century.
Construction and restoration of buildings threaten bats, as they affect nests and can cause habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as do paper flies and chemical treatments used in construction materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren’t really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when they have to catch a prey.
They use a sophisticated echo locating technique to locate insects and obstacles that interfere with their flight.
The National Foundation of Scotland, responsible for taking care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten experts with the proper training, who carry out surveys, inspections of nests and, sometimes, rescues on a regular basis.
The organization has even created Scotland's first and only bat reserve on the Threave Estate, located in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The administrator of the estate, David Thompson, states that it is the ideal territory for the species.
“Here at Threave, we have a big area for bats,” he says.
"We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all good habitat.
But we still don’t know many aspects of bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to grow.”
Notes the importance of checking for bats before performing maintenance tasks on properties, as it may be that the possible involuntary destruction of a single maternity nest kills more than 400 females and young, which could result in the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, attack, annoy and destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an officer at the Scottish Bat Conservation Foundation, has encouraged people to take a step forward to help.
He said: “We still have to learn a lot from bats, and in the case of some of our species, we don’t have enough data on their population.”
