In 1996, a tsunami occurred west of Donggala that killed nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Fire Belt and earthquakes are usually produced there on a certain frequency.
The following are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: On December 26, a major earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Ace province in northern Sumatra triggered a tsunami that affected 14 countries and killed 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of whom in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
