How the U.S.-China Trade War Can Benefit Beijing
Initial salvos from the U.S.-China trade war were deafening and, although the war does not appear to be over soon, a distancing of the countries may prove beneficial for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
U.S. President Donald Trump issued his first warning earlier this year when he imposed taxes on China’s major exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation occurred this week, with new tariffs affecting products worth $200,000 billion. These tariffs involve a tax levy on half of all goods arriving in the U.S. from China.
Beijing has counterattacked each time in the same way and recently raised tariffs from five to ten percent to $60 billion of U.S. goods.
China has pledged to replicate the U.S. and the world’s second-largest economy is unlikely to back down anytime soon.
Getting Washington to back down involves yielding to some demands, but bowing publicly to the U.S. would be too embarrassing for Xi Jinping, the president of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressures of the trade war with the US could benefit China in the long run by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick policy decision in Washington or Beijing could create the conditions that would trigger a fall in any of these countries is far more dangerous than witnesses had predicted,” said Abigail Grace, an Asia-focused research associate at the Center for New American Security, a committee of experts.
Syria 'prepared' for refugees to return, Foreign Minister says
Syria says it is prepared for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help in rebuilding the country, devastated by a war of more than seven years.
In front of the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said conditions in the country are improving.
“Currently, the situation on the street is more stable and secure, thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas that the terrorists destroyed to restore normality.
All conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country that they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and their maintenance are met.
The EU estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the start of the war in 2011.
There are also six million people living in the country who need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem stated that the Syrian regime appreciates any help in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or the help of the countries that financed the insurgency.
